xyz.acygn.mokapot.wireformat

Class ClassNameDescriptions

  • java.lang.Object
    • xyz.acygn.mokapot.wireformat.ClassNameDescriptions

  • public class ClassNameDescriptions
extends Object
    Static methods for handling class name descriptions. A class name description is used to uniquely identify a class in serialised output. It consists of a number (encoded as a sequence of four bytes), possibly plus a sequence of arbitrary bytes; if the number is positive, it refers to the number of bytes, and if the number is negative, there are no additional bytes.

    Note that this class is "pure" in the sense that the output of the functions is recalculated each time. Caching the output of describe is recommended.

    Author:
    Alex Smith

    • Field Detail

      • NULL_DESCRIPTION

        public static final byte[] NULL_DESCRIPTION
        The description of the "class" that null belongs to. In serialised output, it's common to write the class of the object, followed by its fields. This can be used to replace the class of an object in the case where the object turns out to be null.

      • NULL_DESCRIPTION_INT

        public static final int NULL_DESCRIPTION_INT
        The integer used to generate NULL_DESCRIPTION.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • SYNTHETIC_DESCRIPTION

        public static final byte[] SYNTHETIC_DESCRIPTION
        A description indicating that the class the object belongs to was generated at runtime. (In other words, the class does not have a fixed name on disk.) Objects with a class like this can't be serialised in terms of their fields, as there's no way to construct an object of a nonexistent/unknown class, and thus must instead be serialised as the parameters to a factory method.

      • SELFREF_DESCRIPTION

        public static final byte[] SELFREF_DESCRIPTION
        A special case description indicating a reference from an object to an object that references it. Used to serialise cycles of size 2 in serialised output in some special cases.

        This "class name" exists in order to resolve an otherwise problematic case involving Throwable (which is used heavily in error handling code and thus might need to be serialised even when much of the existing code is not working), reducing the number of dependencies required to serialise and deserialise such an object correctly.

      • EXPECTED_DESCRIPTION

        public static final byte[] EXPECTED_DESCRIPTION
        A description indicating the class that the caller believes is "most probable" in context. This would typically be the declared class of the field into which the object described by the class will be deserialised. Its purpose is to avoid the need to parse the name of the class in the common case, whilst still allowing for other actual classes that can fit in the field. (If only one actual class is possible, the class name probably wouldn't need to be described at all.)

    • Method Detail

      • addNewSpecialCaseDescription

        public static void addNewSpecialCaseDescription(int description,
                                                Class<?> described)
                                         throws IllegalArgumentException
        Adds a new special case for producing class name descriptions. In order to prevent a class name being inconsistently described, this must only be called if the class in question has never been described. Typically, a class would add a special-case description from its own static initialiser.
        Parameters:
        description - The desired special-case description. To avoid clashes with other descriptions, this must be less than -0x0D000000.
        described - The class that is described by that description.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the description in question is insufficiently negative or already in use

      • describe

        public static byte[] describe(Class<?> c)
        Produces a description of the name of a class. Each class has a different name description, and the process can be reversed to convert a class name description into the name of the corresponding class.

        This method recalculates the description from scratch each time. If you want to call this repeatedly on potentially the same class, it's a good idea to cache the results.

        Parameters:
        c - The class whose name should be described. This can be any type of class, including an array or unboxed primitive class.
        Returns:
        A description of that class's name. This will be a fresh byte array for each call to this method.

      • specialCasedClass

        public static Class<?> specialCasedClass(int description)
                                  throws IllegalArgumentException
        Translates a negative integer into the corresponding class. Note that this method cannot be used on descriptions that do not refer to a particular class (e.g. "null", "the expected class", "a synthetic class") because those don't have a corresponding Class object; the caller will need to recognise those special cases itself.
        Parameters:
        description - The integer to translate.
        Returns:
        The class referred to by that integer.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the integer is not recognised as referring to any particular class

      • fromByteSlice

        public static Class<?> fromByteSlice(ByteBuffer b)
                              throws ClassNotFoundException
        Converts the trailing portion of a class name description back into a class.
        Parameters:
        b - A byte buffer holding the trailing portion of the description.
        Returns:
        The class matching that description.
        Throws:
        ClassNotFoundException - If the class name encoded in the portion in question does not appear to be a real class
